[h1]Classes[/h1]

As we have seen in the previous modules, built-in data types are used to store a single value in a declared variable. For example,  [b]int  x[/b] stores an integer value in a variable named [b]x[/b].
In object-oriented programming, a [b]class [/b]is a data type that defines a set of variables and methods for a declared [b]object[/b].
 For example, if you were to create a program that manages bank accounts, a [b]BankAccount [/b]class could be used to declare an object that would have all the properties and methods needed for managing an individual bank account, such as a [b]balance [/b]variable and [b]Deposit [/b]and [b]Withdrawal [/b]methods. 

A class is like a [b]blueprint[/b]. It defines the data and behavior for a type. A class definition starts with the keyword [b]class [/b]followed by the class name. The class body contains the data and actions enclosed by curly braces. [code format="cs" ]class BankAccount
{
  //variables, methods, etc.
}[/code]
[note]The class defines a data type for objects, but it is not an object itself. An [b]object [/b]is a concrete entity based on a class, and is sometimes referred to as an [b]instance of a class[/b].[/note]
